\
[A5]\
Whether they are exchanged through the ARP or the ICMP protocols, the packets sent by h1 are exactly the same as the ones received by h3, and vice versa.\
This makes sense because, since h1 and h3 exchange packets between each another, they both see the same packets:\
\
Packet 1: This is the ARP request: the source is h1-eth0\'92s MAC address (6a:df:73:aa:ed:3b) and the destination is Broadcast (all hosts receive this packet), since h1 doesn\'92t know yet who has IP 10.0.0.3.\
Packet 2: Since h3 has the IP requested in the ARP request (10.0.0.3), it replies to the source of the ARP request, which becomes the destination of the reply: h1-eth0\'92s MAC address (6a:df:73:aa:ed:3b). h1 receives this packet.\
Packet 3: Now that h1 has h3 IP address, it can send ICMP echo (ping) request to destination h3, which h3 receives.\
Packet 4: h3 replies to h1 by sending ICMP echo (ping) reply, which h1 receives.\
Steps 3 and 4 keep repeating until we stop the ping program.\
